+Only the first letter of the CLAs matter, so instead of e.g.
 -l lattice.tsam, you could write -lattice lattice.tsam.
+Case does not matter.
+Unless otherwise stated, CLAs are entered as '-x arg' where 
 'x' is the command key and 'arg' is the argument 
+CLAs always overwrite the parameters in the input files

Structure Generation:
-l ..... lattice definition file (default lattice.tsam)
-p ..... infile parameters file (default runparams.tsam)
-w ..... warm-start file 
-r ..... cutoff radius
-n ..... number of total structure gen steps
-d ..... number of decompositions per unique chem env
-s ..... overwritten swapping probabilities
         NOTE: variable number of arguments.  
         ex:  '-s 3 0.5 0.24 0.26' 
         here, '3' is the number of sublattices, followed by
         normalized swapping probabilities for the 0th, 1st, 2nd 
         sublattice.

Simulated annealing: 
-l ..... lattice definition file (default lattice.tsam)
-p ..... infile parameters file (default runparams.tsam)
-e ..... environment file (default envs.tsam)
-r ..... cutoff radius
-n ..... number of total simulated annealing steps
-t ..... beginning thermal energy, eV/site
-s ..... overwritten swapping probabilities
         NOTE: variable number of arguments.  
         ex:  '-s 3 0.5 0.24 0.26' 
         here, '3' is the number of sublattices, followed by
         normalized swapping probabilities for the 0th, 1st, 2nd 
         sublattice.
